text: But let's just say Tesla drops 10%. Tesla drops 10% and you now price down selling puts like 10% down from there. So you're implying a 20% overall move. That's where your model says. Now, day two comes and instead of Tesla going down 5%, it's only down a percent the next day. It was only down 2% the next day. It was down 3% the next day. And the next day it's flat. What you'll realize is you get such high data crush that those wings that you sold, for the high premium, it's pretty gone by now. And you could cover for a pretty well profit if you're fast on it. So it's really aiming to take advantage of that initial shell shock and then capturing that with the data crush that takes place. What we do notice too is we'll get a bounce the next day or the next two days. And then you'll also see that particular contract just literally lose all this premium and we'll exit the trade. However, there's a big disclaimer on this. There are five, six, seven standard deviation moves that take place from time to time. And our book is structured to capture that for the long stuff that we have. So we have risk that is hedged off essentially. And we aim to do this on a sector base. So if we have a particular name that we're doing this on, we absolutely have long fall stuff that is going to be hedging that off. So I don't want any college kid listening to this to think like I could just jump in and start doing this. This is portfolio management. This is how you manage and run a book with interchanging things. It's not on a trade by trade basis where you're saying I like this trade and I like this trade. All these things work together as a balancing act. So if we're losing on the Tesla thing, some of our long ball stuff may step in and may get to points of purpose where they step in and we're making money and that gets hedged off. So nothing is overexposed. We want to make sure we are viewing and assessing our shock levels and our slides and understanding where is our risk. What happens if the market moves down overall 7% and the falls go up six or seven ball points or the market goes up 5% and the ball points go down by five ball points. Let's just say we want to just have a good understanding of where the overall book lies and how it moves from a holistic standpoint. All these trades work together in unison, just like a seesaw.
